.TH "lock_4_inodes" 9 "lock_4_inodes" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
lock_4_inodes \- a wrapper for locking three UBIFS inodes.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "void" lock_4_inodes
.BI "(struct inode *inode1 "  ","
.BI "struct inode *inode2 "  ","
.BI "struct inode *inode3 "  ","
.BI "struct inode *inode4 "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "inode1" 12
first inode
.IP "inode2" 12
second inode
.IP "inode3" 12
third inode
.IP "inode4" 12
fouth inode
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
This function is used for '\fBubifs_rename\fP' and \fIinode1\fP may be the same as
\fIinode2\fP whereas \fIinode3\fP and \fIinode4\fP may be NULL.

We do not implement any tricks to guarantee strict lock ordering, because
VFS has already done it for us on the \fIi_mutex\fP. So this is just a simple
wrapper function.
